    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/vr-001-no-comparator",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Primary hemolysis QoI validation — relative hemolysis index across 5 operating points",
      "description": "CFD-predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values were computed across the five CPB operating points (flow rates 3–6 L/min, rotational speeds 2000–3500 RPM) specified in the COU. Predictions show monotonic sensitivity to impeller tip clearance variation (±0.1 mm), with worst-case NIH occurring at the 3 L/min / 3500 RPM condition. The FDA generic centrifugal blood pump experimental dataset (Hariharan et al.) is cited throughout the validation narrative as the benchmark reference and is described as providing excellent geometric and operational correspondence with the simulation setup. Predicted NIH values fall within the scatter band of the cited experimental data for all five operating points, and the relative hemolysis index RH remains below 1.0 for all nominal-geometry cases. The assessment team notes that the cited dataset has been widely used for CFD hemolysis validation and is considered a high-quality reference. No formal comparedAgainst linkage is recorded for this result; the experimental dataset is referenced discursively in the rationale but not bound as a structured comparator object."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/vr-002-vad-comparator",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Supporting validation — shear-stress distribution against VAD benchmark dataset",
      "description": "Wall shear stress (WSS) and volumetric shear exposure distributions predicted by the CFD model were compared against the Hariharan et al. (2011) FDA benchmark experimental dataset acquired under ventricular assist device (VAD) operating conditions (continuous-flow, long-duration support, cardiac output 5 L/min at 3500 RPM). The pump geometry in the benchmark is identical to the FDA generic centrifugal pump used in this study, and the rotational speed overlaps with the upper end of the CPB operating envelope. Agreement in WSS magnitude and shear-exposure histogram shape is reported as good (mean absolute error < 12%), and this result is presented as corroborating the fidelity of the hemolysis-relevant fluid mechanics in the model. The comparator is formally linked below. Note: the VAD benchmark operates under continuous-flow, chronic-support hemodynamic boundary conditions (higher afterload, lower pulsatility index) that differ systematically from the acute, pulsatile, lower-afterload CPB circuit conditions declared in the COU; this distinction is not examined in the validation narrative.",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/fda-gcbp-experimental-vad-benchmark"
    }
